high temps increase violent behavior

does restricting concealed carry of firearms mitiagte of exacerbate theeffect of temperature on violence

daily variation in temp and variation in gun control policies

more prohibitive laws attenatue the temp-homocide relationship

higher temps act as an exogenous shock

two different research designs, between state differences using Differences in temp, use different areas at the same time with the only difference being concelaed carry laws

also a diff-in-diff-in=temp assumes temp-homocide relationship would be the same under the assumption that temp-homocide relationship would remain the same

they find that gun laws that limit ability to carry firearms mitigate the effect of temp on homicides, find that a 1 c increase in temp is associated with 0.000249 fewer homicides per 100,000 people in more prohibitive pollicy regimes

no relationship with assaults or non-gun homicides

data
- homocides per 100,000 residents from NIBRS
- weather data from PRISM climate group
- concealed carry laws

we already know that confrontations are more likely to occur when its warmer. They argue this depends on concealed carry laws

want to make sure laws don't coincide with other changes or priorities

DiT compares the effect of daily temp fluctuations on homicides between places with different laws

results
- they find orginial temp-homicide relationships as a baseline
- We estimate that a
one-degree Celsius increase in temperature is associated with 0.000511 fewer homicides per
100,000 people during more-prohibitive policy regimes, a 4.2% reduction compared to the
mean.

potential mechanisms
- lethality and displacement: they find that the fewer homocides in places with laws are by guns
- also investigate whether these homicides turn into assaults, no conclusions

could be two ways, increased aggravation or increase social interactions on hot days, but find that aggression is an important mechanism

this has become stronger over time